ORLANDO Pirates supporters want action regarding the investigation into the murder of their late goalkeeper, Senzo Meyiwa.The kasi was echoing to the sound of songs and chanting as supporters marched from Vosloorus Stadium, Ekurhuleni, to the local police station. Dressed in soccer T-shirts, the supporters carried the club&rsquo;s banners and placards with the words: &ldquo;We demand justice&rdquo; and &ldquo;Who killed Senzo?&rdquo;Yesterday marked two years since the death of the Bafana Bafana captain, yet the family are still waiting for answers.Loyal Pirates supporter Philip Jwarha said: &ldquo;We want to see Senzo&rsquo;s murderers behind bars as soon as possible. No one is above the law. We are begging the police to do their job.&rdquo;Another supporter, Themba Maluleke, from the club&rsquo;s Tembisa branch, said they were still mourning the death of the star.&ldquo;We are still in pain.&ldquo;We are angry because the police are dragging their feet on this case,&rdquo; he said.&ldquo;We are not going to let anger control us as Buccaneers, but we have been patient for a long time.&ldquo;All we want is for the killers of Senzo to be brought to book.&rdquo;Station commander at Vosloorus cop shop, Brigadier Themba Denge, received a memorandum from the supporters.&ldquo;I acknowledge receiving this memorandum and I will submit it to the next level of command in the SAPS,&rdquo; he said.Denge said he believed the supporters would soon receive feedback. Senzo died after he was shot during a robbery at his girlfriend&rsquo;s home in Vosloorus in 2014.